            <section id="history" class="section">
                <h2><i class="fas fa-history"></i> History of Iris Flowers</h2>
                <div class="info-section">
                    <div class="info-content">
                        <p>The iris is a genus of 260â€“300 species of flowering plants with showy flowers. It takes its name from the Greek word for a rainbow, which is also the name for the Greek goddess of the rainbow, Iris. Some authors state that the name refers to the wide variety of flower colors found among the many species.</p>
                        
                        <p>Iris flowers have been significant throughout history. In ancient Egypt, the iris was associated with power, with the three petals representing faith, wisdom, and valor. The fleur-de-lis, a stylized iris, first became the symbol of the French monarchy in the 12th century.</p>
                        
                        <div class="timeline">
                            <div class="timeline-item left">
                                <div class="timeline-content">
                                    <div class="timeline-date">Ancient Times</div>
                                    <p>Iris flowers were used in medicinal preparations and perfumes. The root (orris root) was used in aromatherapy and medicine.</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                            <div class="timeline-item right">
                                <div class="timeline-content">
                                    <div class="timeline-date">Middle Ages</div>
                                    <p>The fleur-de-lis became associated with French royalty and remains a symbol in heraldry and design.</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                            <div class="timeline-item left">
                                <div class="timeline-content">
                                    <div class="timeline-date">19th Century</div>
                                    <p>Plant hunters introduced many new iris species to Europe from Asia and the Middle East, leading to extensive hybridization.</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                            <div class="timeline-item right">
                                <div class="timeline-content">
                                    <div class="timeline-date">1936</div>
                                    <p>Ronald Fisher used the Iris flower data set in his paper on linear discriminant analysis, making it famous in statistics.</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        
                        <p>Today, iris species are found in temperate regions throughout the world, from Europe to Asia, across North America, and throughout the Middle East. The Iris flower data set or Fisher's Iris data set is a multivariate data set introduced by the British statistician and biologist Ronald Fisher in his 1936 paper.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </section>
            
            <section id="species" class="section">
                <h2><i class="fas fa-seedling"></i> Iris Species Details</h2>
                <div class="info-section">
                    <h3>Iris Setosa</h3>
                    <div class="info-content">
                        <p>Iris setosa is a species in the genus Iris, it is also in the subgenus Limniris and in the series Tripetalae. It is a rhizomatous perennial from a wide range across the Arctic sea, including Alaska, Maine, Canada, Russia, northeastern Asia, China, Korea and southwards to Japan.</p>
                        <p>The plant has tall branching stems, mid green leaves and vibrant flowers in shades of blue, purple, and occasionally white. It is one of the hardiest irises, able to withstand cold temperatures and harsh conditions.</p>
                    </div>
                    
                    <h3>Iris Versicolor</h3>
                    <div class="info-content">
                        <p>Iris versicolor is also commonly known as the blue flag, harlequin blueflag, larger blue flag, northern blue flag, and poison flag, plus other variations of these names, and in Britain and Ireland as purple iris.</p>
                        <p>It is a species of Iris native to North America, in the Eastern United States and Eastern Canada. It is common in sedge meadows, marshes, and along streambanks and shores. The specific epithet versicolor means "variously coloured".</p>
                    </div>
                    
                    <h3>Iris Virginica</h3>
                    <div class="info-content">
                        <p>Iris virginica, with the common name Virginia iris, is a perennial species of flowering plant, native to eastern North America. It is common along the coastal plain from Florida to Georgia in the Southeastern United States.</p>
                        <p>It is cultivated as an ornamental plant in temperate regions. It is one of the three Iris species in the Iris flower data set outlined by Ronald Fisher in his 1936 paper "The use of multiple measurements in taxonomic problems".</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </section>
            
